<ns2926:section xmlns:ns2926="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.concepts.architecture.mda.introduction.history">

  <ns2927:title xmlns:ns2927="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">History of the MDA</ns2927:title>
  <ns2928:para xmlns:ns2928="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    <ns2929:itemizedlist xmlns:ns2929="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
      <ns2930:listitem xmlns:ns2930="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2931:para xmlns:ns2931="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        Both, the UML and MOF standards were published by the OMG in 1997.  
      </ns2931:para></ns2930:listitem>
      <ns2932:listitem xmlns:ns2932="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2933:para xmlns:ns2933="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        In November 2000 the OMG published a white paper which proposed the MDA as 
        way to address the confusion and model instabilities caused by the rapid development
        and proliferation of middleware platforms.
      </ns2933:para></ns2932:listitem>
      <ns2934:listitem xmlns:ns2934="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2935:para xmlns:ns2935="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        Work on the MDA began in February 2001.  
      </ns2935:para></ns2934:listitem>
      <ns2936:listitem xmlns:ns2936="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2937:para xmlns:ns2937="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        MDA version 1.0 was published in May 2003.  
      </ns2937:para></ns2936:listitem>
      <ns2938:listitem xmlns:ns2938="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns2939:para xmlns:ns2939="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        Large companies expecting to become MDA tool vendors have since then contributed to the
        UML version 2.0 specification process including features which explicitly support aspects
        of the MDA.
      </ns2939:para></ns2938:listitem>
    </ns2929:itemizedlist>
  </ns2928:para>
</ns2926:section>